		{"id":"6b3163d21701cbd7","type":"text","text":"# How your frontend stack works (end to end)\n\nThis is the flow on your **Tech stack — frontend** slide, explained as a **process** from code to what the user sees.\n\n---\n\n## The full pipeline\n\n```text\nTypeScript (.ts / .tsx)\n        │\n        ├── React        → UI structure + state\n        ├── Tailwind CSS → styling (utility classes)\n        └── shadcn/ui    → pre-built Button, Card, etc.\n                │\n                ▼\n        Next.js  → pages, API routes, SSR, build\n                │\n                ▼\n        Node.js  → dev server · CI build · Vercel runtime\n                │\n                ▼\n        Browser  → user sees and clicks the UI\n```\n\n---\n\n## Step 1 — TypeScript (`.ts` and `.tsx`)\n\nYou write typed code so mistakes are caught early.\n\n| File | Role |\n|------|------|\n| `.ts` | Logic only — services, forecast math, Plaid client |\n| `.tsx` | UI — JSX + TypeScript (pages, components) |\n\nExample: `PlaidBankActions.tsx` handles “Connect bank”; `orchestrator.ts` handles chat routing (no UI).\n\n---\n\n## Step 2 — React (UI library)\n\nReact builds the interface as **components** — reusable pieces with **state** (data that changes).\n\n```tsx\nconst [busy, setBusy] = useState(false);\n<button disabled={busy}>Connect bank</button>\n```\n\nWhen `busy` changes, React updates the button automatically.  \nPages like `/ledger`, `/balances`, `/simulation` are built from many components.\n\n---\n\n## Step 3 — Tailwind CSS (styling)\n\nInstead of separate CSS files, you style with **utility classes** in JSX:\n\n```tsx\nclassName=\"border-teal-500/30 bg-teal-500/10 text-teal-800\"\n```\n\nThat’s how route badges in `ChatResultView.tsx` get their colors — fast, consistent styling.\n\n---\n\n## Step 4 — shadcn/ui (pre-built components)\n\n**shadcn/ui** is not an npm “black box” library — you copy **Button**, **Card**, **Input** into `components/ui/`.  \nThey’re already **React + Tailwind**, so the app looks consistent (ledger forms, chat, Plaid panel).\n\n---\n\n## Step 5 — Next.js (framework)\n\nNext.js wraps React and adds what a real app needs:\n\n| Feature | In your app |\n|---------|-------------|\n| **Routing** | `/ledger`, `/balances`, `/simulation` → folders under `app/` |\n| **API routes** | `/api/scenario-chat`, `/api/integrations/plaid/...` — backend on same project |\n| **SSR** | Server builds HTML first; user sees content quickly |\n| **Build** | `npm run build` → production bundle for Vercel |\n\nSo: **React = UI**, **Next.js = app shell + server + URLs + APIs**.\n\n---\n\n## Step 6 — Node.js (runtime)\n\n**Node.js** runs JavaScript/TypeScript **outside the browser**.\n\n| When | What Node does |\n|------|----------------|\n| **Local dev** | `npm run dev` → Next.js dev server on port 3000 |\n| **CI (GitHub Actions)** | `npm test`, `npm run build` |\n| **Production (Vercel)** | Runs Next.js server + API routes when users visit your site |\n\nYour forecast and Plaid logic run on **Node on Vercel**, not in the user’s browser (secrets stay server-side).\n\n---\n\n## Step 7 — Browser (what the user sees)\n\n1. User opens `household-financial-web.vercel.app`\n2. Server sends HTML (SSR) + JavaScript bundles\n3. React **hydrates** — page becomes interactive\n4. **Client components** (`\"use client\"`) handle clicks, Plaid Link, mic, chat\n\n```text\nServer (Node/Vercel)     Browser\n─────────────────        ───────\nLoad ledger data    →    Show /ledger page\nAPI /scenario-chat  ←    User asks “Can we afford…?”\n                         Plaid Link opens in browser\n```\n\n---\n\n## One example: “Ask AI” on `/simulation`\n\n```text\n1. User types question in ForecastSimulator.tsx (React + shadcn Button)\n2. Browser fetch → POST /api/scenario-chat (Next.js API route on Node)\n3. orchestrator.ts runs routing (deterministic / LangGraph / RAG)\n4. JSON response → ChatResultView shows badge + answer (React)\n5. Tailwind styles the LangGraph / ledger badges\n```\n\n---\n\n## 30-second version for your talk\n\n> We write **TypeScript** in **React** components, styled with **Tailwind** and **shadcn**. **Next.js** gives us pages, API routes, and server rendering. **Node** runs that locally, in CI, and on **Vercel**. The **browser** shows the UI and handles interactive pieces like Plaid and voice — while money logic stays on the server.\n\n---\n\n## How the slide layers fit together\n\n| Layer             | One phrase                             |\n| ----------------- | -------------------------------------- |\n| React             | **What** the UI is (components, state) |\n| Tailwind + shadcn | **How** it looks                       |\n| Next.js           | **How** pages and APIs are wired       |\n| Node.js           | **Where** it runs                      |\n| Browser           | **Who** uses it                        |\n\n","x":-780,"y":-720,"width":1100,"height":1020}
	],
